failed_tasks.reason: Critique: Try commands like "look at mat" or "examine rubber mat" and check for a descriptive response from the game. If nothing appears, ensure you are in the correct location where the mat is present.
Critique: Try using "move leaves" (if not already done), then "open grating" or "lift grating" again. If it's locked, try to find a key or another way to unlock it before opening.
Critique: Try using "look at nest" or "examine small birds nest" to get a description. If that fails, try "look" to get a general room description that might mention the nest.
Critique: Try opening the egg, shaking it, or using "look closely at egg" to see if more details or a hidden description can be revealed.
Critique: Try "go east" again, or use "look" after each move to check if you've reached the clearing. If you see a description mentioning a clearing, you'll know you've arrived.

Critique: Try using more standard movement commands such as "down," "d," or "go down" to descend into the canyon. Alternatively, look for a specific path or object that allows descent, such as "climb rope" or "go path."

Critique: Try examining the nest in a different location, or use commands like "look under nest" or "search inside nest" to reveal more details. If the nest is in your inventory, try dropping it and examining it again.
Critique: Try using commands like "open birds nest" or "examine inside nest" to prompt the game to reveal its contents or confirm if it can be opened.
Critique: Try exploring for a key or another way into the house, such as looking for a window or another entrance. You might also try examining the door more closely for clues.
Critique: Try "look at mat" or "examine rubber mat" to prompt the game to provide a description. If that fails, try "look under mat" to see if anything is hidden there.
Critique: Try examining the surrounding area or using alternate commands like "look under grating" or "open grating" to see if more detail can be revealed.
Critique: Try going east again from your current location to see if it leads to the clearing. If not, consider retracing your steps and looking for another route east toward the clearing.

Critique: Try using directional movement commands like "up" or "u", or look for alternate exits (e.g., "go north" if a path is mentioned). If climbing is possible, the game may require a specific command or may only allow climbing at a particular spot. Try "climb up wall" or "go up".

Critique: Try "examine jewel-encrusted egg" or "look at jewel-encrusted egg" and check if the game provides a description. If it still does not, try examining it in a different location or after making progress in the story.

Critique: Try "put egg in birds nest" or "place egg in nest" while both the egg and nest are present in the same location. Make sure you are not carrying the nest—drop it first if necessary, then put the egg in it.

Critique: Try examining the nest in a different location, or use commands like "look inside nest" or "search nest" if not already attempted. If the nest is in your inventory, try dropping it and then examining it again.
Critique: Try using "go west" or "walk across rainbow" again, or look for another way to cross the rainbow (perhaps examine the surroundings for clues or try "climb rainbow").
Critique: Try using "look at nest" or "inventory" to see if the game provides a description. If that fails, try "examine egg" or "look in birds nest" if you suspect there is something inside.

Critique: Try using "go up," "climb up," or look for another path or object (like a rope or ledge) that might allow you to ascend the cliff. Consider examining your surroundings for hidden routes or tools.

    In ZORK the intrepid explorer delves into the forgotten secrets of a lost labyrinth deep in the bowels of the earth, searching for vast treasures long hidden from prying eyes, treasures guarded by fearsome monsters and diabolical traps!

    No PDP-10 should be without one!

It was inspired by the ADVENTURE game of Crowther and Woods, and the long tradition of fantasy and science fiction adventure.  ZORK was originally written in MDL (alias MUDDLE). Up a Tree
You are about 10 feet above the ground nestled among some large branches.  The nearest branch above you is above your reach.
On the branch is a small birds nest.
In the bird's nest is a large egg encrusted with precious jewels, apparently scavenged somewhere by a childless songbird.  The egg is covered with fine gold inlay, and ornamented in lapis lazuli and mother-of-pearl.  Unlike most eggs, this one is hinged and has a delicate looking clasp holding it closed.  The egg appears extremely fragile.

Canyon View
You are at the top of the Great Canyon on its south wall.  From here there is a marvelous view of the Canyon and parts of the Frigid River upstream.  Across the canyon, the walls of the White Cliffs still appear to loom far above.  Following the Canyon upstream (north and northwest), Aragain Falls may be seen, complete with rainbow. Fortunately, my vision is better than average and I can discern the top of the Flood Control Dam #3 far to the distant north.  To the west and south can be seen an immense forest, stretching for miles around.  It is possible to climb down into the canyon from here.

    ZORK is a game of adventure, danger, and low cunning.  In it you will explore some of the most amazing territory ever seen by mortal man.  Hardened adventurers have run screaming from the terrors contained within!

    In ZORK the intrepid explorer delves into the forgotten secrets of a lost labyrinth deep in the bowels of the earth, searching for vast treasures long hidden from prying eyes, treasures guarded by fearsome monsters and diabolical traps!

    No PDP-10 should be without one!

    ZORK was created at the MIT Laboratory for Computer Science, by Tim Anderson, Marc Blank, Bruce Daniels, and Dave Lebling.  It was inspired by the ADVENTURE game of Crowther and Woods, and the long tradition of fantasy and science fiction adventure.  ZORK was originally written in MDL (alias MUDDLE).  The current version was translated from MDL into Inform by Ethan Dicks <erd@infinet.com>.

>                                                                                                                                Rocky LedgeScore: 5Moves: 340

Canyon View
You are at the top of the Great Canyon on its south wall.  From here there is a marvelous view of the Canyon and parts of the Frigid River upstream.  Across the canyon, the walls of the White Cliffs still appear to loom far above.  Following the Canyon upstream (north and northwest), Aragain Falls may be seen, complete with rainbow. Fortunately, my vision is better than average and I can discern the top of the Flood Control Dam #3 far to the distant north.  To the west and south can be seen an immense forest, stretching for miles around.  It is possible to climb down into the canyon from here.
